trans-unit.source: Defines the swapping strategy for algorithms that need to swap elements in a range (such as partition and sort). The strategy concerns the swapping of elements that are not the core concern of the algorithm. For example, consider an algorithm that sorts [ "abc", "b", "aBc" ] according to toUpper(a) < toUpper(b). That algorithm might choose to swap the two equivalent strings "abc" and "aBc". That does not affect the sorting since both ["abc", "aBc", "b" ] and [ "aBc", "abc", "b" ] are valid outcomes.

trans-unit.source: Determines the boundary between valid and invalid addresses. Status codes above this number will be returned as-is, status codes below will be returned as EmailStatusCode.valid. Thus the calling program can simply look for EmailStatusCode.valid if it is only interested in whether an address is valid or not. The errorLevel will determine how "picky" isEmail() is about the address. If omitted or passed as EmailStatusCode.none then isEmail() will not perform any finer grained error checking and an address is either considered valid or not. trans-unit.source: Do not use byte-by-byte memory copies to copy pointer values. This may result in intermediate conditions where there is not a valid pointer, and if the gc pauses the thread in such a condition, it can corrupt memory. Most implementations of memcpy() will work since the internal implementation of it does the copy in aligned chunks greater than or equal to the pointer size, but since this kind of implementation is not guaranteed by the C standard, use memcpy() only with extreme caution.

trans-unit.source: Each tracked pointer is in one of the following states:

Eager parallel map. The eagerness of this function means it has less overhead than the lazily evaluated TaskPool.map and should be preferred where the memory requirements of eagerness are acceptable. functions are the functions to be evaluated, passed as template alias parameters in a style similar to std.algorithm.iteration.map. The first argument must be a random access range. For performance reasons, amap will assume the range elements have not yet been initialized. Elements will be overwritten without calling a destructor nor doing an assignment. As such, the range must not contain meaningful data: either un-initialized objects, or objects in their .init state.
trans-unit.target: Ansioso mapa paralelo. El afán de esta función significa que tiene menos sobrecarga que el TaskPool.map evaluado perezosamente y debe preferirse donde los requisitos de memoria del afán son aceptables. functions son las funciones a evaluar, pasadas como parámetros de alias de plantilla en un estilo similar a std.algorithm.iteration.map . El primer argumento debe ser un rango de acceso aleatorio. Por razones de rendimiento, amap asumirá que los elementos del rango aún no se han inicializado. Los elementos se sobrescribirán sin llamar a un destructor ni realizar una tarea. Como tal, el rango no debe contener datos significativos: objetos no inicializados u objetos en su estado .init .

trans-unit.source: Encodes edit operations necessary to transform one sequence into another. Given sequences s (source) and t (target), a sequence of EditOp encodes the steps that need to be taken to convert s into t. For example, if s = "cat" and "cars", the minimal sequence that transforms s into t is: skip two characters, replace 't' with 'r', and insert an 's'. Working with edit operations is useful in applications such as spell-checkers (to find the closest word to a given misspelled word), approximate searches, diff-style programs that compute the difference between files, efficient encoding of patches, DNA sequence analysis, and plagiarism detection.
trans-unit.target: Codifica las operaciones de edición necesarias para transformar una secuencia en otra. Dadas las secuencias s (fuente) t (destino), una secuencia de EditOp codifica los pasos que deben seguirse para convertir s en t . Por ejemplo, si s = "cat" y "cars" , la secuencia mínima que transforma s en t es: omita dos caracteres, reemplace 't' con 'r' e inserte una 's'. Trabajar con operaciones de edición es útil en aplicaciones como correctores ortográficos (para encontrar la palabra más cercana a una palabra mal escrita), búsquedas aproximadas, programas de estilo diff que calculan la diferencia entre archivos, codificación eficiente de parches, análisis de secuencia de ADN y detección de plagio.
